I thought that initializing a [`std::optional`][1] with [`std::nullopt`][2] would be the same as default construction.

[They are described as the same at cppreference][3], as form (1)

However, both Clang and GCC seem to treat these toy example functions differently.

    #include &lt;optional&gt;
    
    struct Data {
        char large_data[0x10000];
    };
    
    std::optional&lt;Data&gt; nullopt_init() {
      return std::nullopt;
    }
    
    std::optional&lt;Data&gt; default_init() {
      return {};
    }

[Compiler Explorer seems to imply][4] that using `std::nullopt` will simply set the &quot;contains&quot; flag,

    nullopt_init():
        mov     BYTE PTR [rdi+65536], 0
        mov     rax, rdi
        ret

While default construction will value initialize the entire class.  This is functionally equivalent, but almost always costlier.

    default_init():
        sub     rsp, 8
        mov     edx, 65537
        xor     esi, esi
        call    memset
        add     rsp, 8
        ret

**Is this intentional behavior?  When should one form be preferred over the other?**


